# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bristol-407
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The company was created following Armstrong Whitworth 's purchase of Siddeley-Deasy, a manufacturer of luxury motor cars marketed to the top echelon of society.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] After the merger of companies, this focus on quality continued throughout in the production of cars, aircraft engines, gearboxes for tanks and buses, rocket and torpedo motors, and the development of railcars.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Company mergers and takeovers with Hawker Aviation and Bristol Aero Engines enabled the continuation of car production, which had ceased in August 1960.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The company was absorbed into the Rolls-Royce conglomerate, which was interested in the aircraft and aircraft engine business.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Eventually, the remaining spares and all motor car interests were sold to the Armstrong Siddeley Owners Club Ltd, which now owns the patents, designs, copyrights, and trademarks, including the name Armstrong Siddeley.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Considered "an elegant car appropriate for royal use", the "Armstrong Siddeley Saloon" was used by the Prince of Wales (later King Edward VIII) during his 1930 tour of Uganda.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The Siddeley Autocar Company, of Coventry, was founded by John Davenport Siddeley (1866–1953) in 1902.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Its products, made for him by a Vickers subsidiary, were heavily based on Peugeots using many Peugeot parts and fitted with English-built bodies.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Siddeley was appointed London sales manager of Vickers Limited's subsidiary Wolseley in early 1905 at the same time as Wolseley purchased the goodwill and patent rights of his Siddeley car.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] A few months later Herbert Austin left to form his own business and Siddeley was appointed general manager.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Without the consent of the Vickers brothers Siddeley added his own name to the Wolseley nameplate but it was dropped on his departure.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Siddeley resigned from Wolseley and in 1910, he took on management of The Deasy Motor Car Manufacturing Company, Limited.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The shareholders were so pleased with his success in that post that on 7 November 1912 they unanimously agreed to change the company's name to The Siddeley-Deasy Motor Car Company Limited.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Siddeley's name had been added to the product's radiator earlier in 1912.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] His cars began to use the slogan "As silent as the Sphinx", sporting a Sphinx as a bonnet mascot.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In April 1919, Siddeley-Deasy was bought out by Armstrong Whitworth Development Company of Newcastle upon Tyne and in May 1919 became Armstrong Siddeley Motors Ltd, a subsidiary with J.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1927, Armstrong Whitworth merged its heavy engineering interests with Vickers to form Vickers-Armstrongs.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Siddeley brought Armstrong Siddeley and Armstrong Whitworth Aircraft into his control.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1928, Armstrong Siddeley Holdings bought Avro from Crossley Motors.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Also that year Siddeley partnered with Walter Gordon Wilson, inventor of the pre-selector gearbox, to create Improved Gears Ltd, which later became Self-Changing Gears – the gearbox that should be credited with enabling the marketing tagline "Cars for the daughters of gentlemen".
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Armstrong Siddeley manufactured luxury cars, aircraft engines, and later, aircraft.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Siddeley's interests were purchased for £2 million by aviation pioneer Tommy Sopwith, owner of Hawker Aircraft, to form – along with the Gloster Aircraft Company and Air Training Services – Hawker Siddeley, a famous name in British aircraft production.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Armstrong Whitworth Aircraft and Armstrong Siddeley Motors became subsidiaries of Hawker Siddeley, with Sopwith himself becoming the new chairman of Armstrong Siddeley Motors.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] At this time, there remained an "unbroken business association" between the Siddeley family and the Middleton-Joy family who were manufactures of Filtrate Oil and had enjoyed considerable success in car-racing rallies.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Armstrong Siddeley was merged with the aircraft engine business of Bristol Aeroplane Company (Bristol Aero Engines) to form Bristol Siddeley as part of an ongoing rationalisation under government influence of the British aircraft and aircraft engine manufacturers.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Armstrong Siddeley produced their last cars in 1960.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Bristol Siddeley and Rolls-Royce merged in 1966, the latter subsuming the former which remained for a while as an aircraft engine division within Rolls-Royce.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In June 1972, Rolls-Royce (1972) Ltd sold all the stock of spares plus all patents, specifications, drawings, catalogues and the name of Armstrong Siddeley Motors Ltd to the Armstrong Siddeley Owners Club Ltd.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] This meant that "Armstrong Siddeley" and "A-S Sphinx Logo" are trademarks and copyright of the Armstrong Siddeley Owners Club Ltd.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The "Siddeley" name survived a while longer in aviation, through Hawker Siddeley Aviation and Hawker Siddeley Dynamics.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1977 they joined with others to become British Aerospace (BAe) which with further mergers is now BAE Systems.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The first car produced from the union was a fairly massive machine, a 5-litre 30 hp.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] A smaller 18 hp appeared in 1922 and a 2-litre 14 hp was introduced in 1923.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] 1928 saw the company's first 15 hp six; 1929 saw the introduction of a 12 hp vehicle.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] This was a pioneering year for the marque, during which it first offered the Wilson preselector gearbox as an optional extra; it became standard issue on all cars from 1933.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1930 the company marketed four models, of 12, 15, 20, and 30 hp, the last costing £1450.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The company's rather staid image was endorsed during the 1930s by the introduction of a range of six-cylinder cars with ohv engines, though a four-cylinder 12 hp was kept in production until 1936.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1932 - or thereabouts, a line of special, rather more sporty designs was started which resulted in the Rally Tourer series.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The aim was to help shake off the somewhat pedestrian image of what was in fact a rather advanced product.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Of the 16 rally tourers built, many were used by the owners or senior directors, and were entered into various rallies, achieving some good results and making for good publicity.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Only one of those 16 special cars is now known to exist: a 1933, Long-15 Rally Tourer which, according to the records, shared the same body as the 20 hp version (which had a slightly longer bonnet).
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1933, the 5-litre six-cylinder Siddeley Special was announced, featuring a Hiduminium aluminium alloy engine; this model cost £950.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Car production continued at a reduced rate throughout 1940, and a few were assembled in 1941.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The week that World War II ended in Europe, Armstrong Siddeley introduced its first post-war models; these were the Lancaster four-door saloon and the Hurricane drophead coupe.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The names of these models echoed the names of aircraft produced by the Hawker Siddeley Group (the name adopted by the company in 1935) during the war.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] These cars all used a 2-litre six-cylinder (16 hp) engines, increased to 2.3-litre (18 hp) engines in 1949.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] From 1949 to 1952 two commercial variants of the 18 hp Whitleys were produced, primarily for export.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The Utility Coupé was a conventional coupe utility style vehicle, while the Station Coupé was effectively a dual cab vehicle, although it still retained only two doors.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] However, it did have two rows of seating to accommodate up to four adults and the doors were larger to allow better access to the rear.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] From 1953 the company produced the Sapphire, with a 3.4-litre six-cylinder engine.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1956, the model range was expanded with the addition of the 234 (a 2.3-litre four-cylinder) and the 236 (with the older 2.3-litre six-cylinder engine).
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The Sapphire 346 sported a bonnet mascot in the shape of a sphinx with namesake Armstrong Siddeley Sapphire jet engines attached.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The 234 and 236 Sapphires might have looked to some of marque's loyal customers like a radical departure from the traditional Armstrong Siddeley appearance.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] However, in truth, they were simply too conservative in a period of rapidly developing automotive design.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] If the "baby Sapphire" heralded the beginning of the end for Armstrong Siddeley, it was because Jaguar had launched the unitary-construction 2.4 saloon in 1955, which was quicker, significantly cheaper, and much better-looking than the 234 and 236.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The last new model produced by Armstrong Siddeley was 1958's Star Sapphire, with a 4-litre engine, and automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The Armstrong Siddeley was a casualty of the 1960 merger with Bristol; the last car left the Coventry factory in 1960.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Cars produced by Armstrong Siddeley had designations that came from the tax horsepower rating of their engines.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] A feature of many of their later cars was the option of an electrically controlled pre-selector gearbox.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Like many British cars of this era, there are active owners' clubs supporting their continued use in several countries, e.g. the UK, Australia, New Zealand, the Netherlands and Germany.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Armstrong Siddeley Owners Club Ltd has members worldwide and many members of the ASCC in Australia are resident overseas.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In the United Kingdom, ASOC publishes a monthly members magazine *Sphinx*.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In Australia, the Armstrong Siddeley Car Club publishes *Southern Sphinx* six times a year.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In the Netherlands, ASOC Dutch also publishes six times a year, and in New Zealand, Armstrong Siddeley Car Club in New Zealand Inc. publish *Sphinx-NZ* monthly.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Throughout the 1920s and 1930s, Armstrong Siddeley produced a range of low- and mid-power aircraft radial engines, all named after big cats.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] They also produced a tiny 2-cylinder engine called the Ounce, another name for the snow leopard, for ultralight aircraft.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The company started work on their first gas turbine engine in 1939, following the design pioneered at the Royal Aircraft Establishment by Alan Arnold Griffith.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Known as the "ASX" for "Armstrong Siddeley eXperimental", the original pure-turbojet design was later adapted to drive a propeller, resulting in the "ASP".
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] From then on, AS turbine engines were named after snakes.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The Mamba and Double Mamba were turboprop engines, the latter being a complex piece of engineering with two side-by-side Mambas driving through a common gearbox, and could be found on the Fairey Gannet.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The Python turboprop powered the Westland Wyvern strike aircraft.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Further development of the Mamba removed the reduction gearbox to give the Adder turbojet.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Another pioneer in the production of the RAE engine design was Metrovick, who started with a design known as the Metrovick F.2.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] This engine never entered production, and Metrovick turned to a larger design, the Beryl, and then to an even larger design, the Sapphire.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Armstrong Siddeley later took over the Sapphire design, and it went on to be one of the most successful 2nd generation jet engines, competing with the better-known Rolls-Royce Avon.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The company went on to develop an engine – originally for unmanned Jindivik target drones – called the Viper.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] This product was further developed by Bristol Siddeley and, later, Rolls-Royce and was sold in great numbers over many years.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] A range of rocket motors were also produced, including the Snarler and Stentor.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The rocket development complemented that of Bristol, and Bristol Siddeley would become the leading British manufacturer of rocket engines for missiles.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1946 Armstrong Siddeley produced their first diesel engines.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] They were medium-speed engines for industrial and agricultural use.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Initially there was a single-cylinder engine producing 5 bhp (3.7 kW) at 900 rpm and a twin-cylinder version.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Each cylinder had a capacity of 988 cm3 (60.2 cubic inches).
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The power output and speed was progressively increased.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] By the end of 1954 the single-cylinder engine was rated at 11 bhp (8.2 kW) at 1800 rpm and the twin-cylinder engine 22 bhp (16 kW) at the same speed.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In 1955 the range was extended with the introduction of a 3-cylinder engine rated at 33 bhp (25 kW).
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The engines were built at Armstrong Siddeley's factory at Walnut Street in Leicester until that factory closed in August 1957.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Production was transferred to the factory of Armstrong Siddeley (Brockworth) Ltd in Gloucestershire and in 1958 to the factory of Petters Limited at Staines, Middlesex.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] The engines built by Petters were designated AS1, AS2 and AS3 to distinguish them from that company's other products.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Production ended in 1962 when Petters introduced a replacement range of lightweight small high-speed air-cooled diesel engines.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] In April 1958 the company obtained a licence to build the Maybach MD series high-speed diesel engines.
[src:bristol-407/armstrong-siddeley] Several hundred were built by Bristol Siddeley Engines Ltd after that company took over Armstrong Siddeley's manufacturing activities in 1959.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:bristol-407/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW AG's automobiles are marketed under the BMW, Mini, and Rolls-Royce brands while its motorcycles are marketed under the BMW Motorrad brand.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2023, BMW became the world's ninth-largest producer of motor vehicles (with 2,555,341 vehicles made in that year alone) as well as the 6th largest automaker by revenue.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2023, it was ranked 46th in the *Forbes* Global 2000.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The company also has significant motor-sport history, especially in touring cars, sports cars, and the Isle of Man TT.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW initially focused on aircraft engine production during World War I, a legacy that influenced the company's engineering emphasis on performance and precision.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Known as "The Ultimate Driving Machine", the brand is celebrated for engineering vehicles that blend high-end luxury with sharp, driver-focused performance.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Following postwar restrictions on aircraft manufacturing, BMW diversified into motorcycle production in the 1920s and later entered the automobile market, establishing itself as a major player in the automotive industry.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW AG is headquartered in Munich and produces motor vehicles in Germany, United Kingdom, United States, Brazil, Mexico, South Africa, India, and China.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The Quandt family is a long-term shareholder of the company, following investments by the brothers Herbert and Harald Quandt in 1959 which saved BMW from bankruptcy, with remaining shares owned by the public.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW traces its origins to aircraft engine manufacturer Otto Flugmaschinenfabrik, founded in 1910 by Gustav Otto in the Kingdom of Bavaria, then part of the German Empire.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] On 18 August 1916, the firm was reorganized as Bayerische Flugzeugwerke (BFW).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 1922, BFW was renamed Bayerische Motoren Werke (BMW).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The name BMW, however, had earlier been used by a company founded in 1913 by Karl Rapp as Rapp Motorenwerke.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 1922, the name and engine-production assets of Rapp Motorenwerke were transferred to Bayerische Flugzeugwerke, which adopted the BMW name in the same year.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW's first products were aircraft engines for the Luftstreitkräfte.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] One of its early designs was the BMW IIIa, a straight-six engine developed in 1917 by engineer Max Friz.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] After World War I, BMW diversified into the production of motorcycle engines, agricultural equipment, household items, and railway brakes.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 1923, the company introduced its first motorcycle, the BMW R32.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW became an automobile manufacturer in 1928 following its acquisition of Fahrzeugfabrik Eisenach, which produced the Austin 7 under licence from Austin Motor Company, marketed as the Dixi.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The first car sold as a BMW was the BMW 3/15, a rebadged version of the Dixi.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] During the 1930s, BMW expanded its product range to include sports cars and larger luxury vehicles.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Aircraft engines, motorcycles, and automobiles would be BMW's main products until World War II.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] During the war, BMW concentrated on building the BMW 801 aircraft engine using as many as 40,000 slave laborers.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] These consisted primarily of prisoners from Nazi concentration camps, most prominently Dachau.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Motorcycles remained as a side-line and automobile manufacture ceased altogether.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW's factories were heavily bombed during the war and its remaining West German facilities were banned from producing motor vehicles or aircraft after the war.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The company survived by making pots, pans, and bicycles.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 1948, BMW restarted motorcycle production.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW resumed car production in Bavaria in 1952 with the BMW 501 luxury saloon.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The range of cars was expanded in 1955, through the production of the cheaper Isetta microcar under licence.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Slow sales of luxury cars and small profit margins from microcars, meant BMW was in serious financial trouble and in 1959 the company was nearly taken over by rival Daimler-Benz.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] A large investment in BMW by Herbert Quandt and Harald Quandt resulted in the company surviving as a separate entity.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Günther Quandt was a well-known German industrialist and joined the Nazi Party in 1933; he made a fortune arming the *Wehrmacht*, manufacturing weapons and batteries.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Many of his enterprises were appropriated from Jewish owners under duress with minimal compensation.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] At least three of his enterprises made extensive use of slave laborers, as many as 50,000 in all.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] One of his battery factories had its own on-site concentration camp, complete with gallows.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Life expectancy for laborers was six months.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] While Quandt and BMW were not directly connected during the war, funds amassed in the Nazi era by his father allowed Herbert Quandt to buy BMW.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The relative success of the small BMW 700 assisted in the company's recovery, allowing them to develop the New Class sedans.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The 1962 introduction of the BMW New Class compact sedans was the beginning of BMW's reputation as a leading manufacturer of sport-oriented cars.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Throughout the 1960s, BMW expanded its range by adding coupé and luxury sedan models.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The BMW 5 Series mid-size sedan range was introduced in 1972, followed by the BMW 3 Series compact sedans in 1975, the BMW 6 Series luxury coupés in 1976 and the BMW 7 Series large luxury sedans in 1978.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The BMW M division released its first road car, the M1, a mid-engine supercar, in 1978.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] This was followed by the BMW M5 in 1984 and the BMW M3 in 1986.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Also in 1986, BMW introduced its first V12 engine in the 750i luxury sedan.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The 1989 BMW Z1 marked BMW's return to making a two-seat roadster, the 1995 BMW Z3 was their first mass-production two-seat roadster, and the 1999 BMW X5 was the company's first entry into the SUV market.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The company purchased the Rover Group in 1994, but the takeover was not successful and caused BMW large financial losses.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2000, BMW sold off most of the Rover brands, retaining only the Mini brand.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 1998, BMW also acquired the rights to the Rolls-Royce brand from Vickers.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW's first modern mass-produced turbocharged petrol engine was introduced in 2006 (from 1973 to 1975, BMW built 1,672 units of a turbocharged BMW M10 engine for the BMW 02 Series), with most engines switching over to turbocharging over the 2010s.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The first hybrid BMW was the 2010 BMW ActiveHybrid 7, and BMW's first mass-production electric car was the BMW i3 city car, which was released in 2013, (from 1968 to 1972, BMW built two battery-electric BMW 1602 Elektro saloons for the 1972 Olympic Games).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] After many years of establishing a reputation for sporting rear-wheel drive cars, BMW's first front-wheel drive car was the 2014 BMW 2 Series Active Tourer multi-purpose vehicle (MPV).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In March 2018, Daimler and BMW merged their mobility services.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In August 2019, Oliver Zipse replaced Harald Krüger as the head of the BMW Group..
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In May 2026, Milan Nedeljković succeeded Zipse as chairman of the board of management of BMW AG.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In January 2021, BMW announced that its sales in 2020 fell by 8.4 percent due to the impact of COVID-19 pandemic restrictions.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] However, in the fourth quarter of 2020, BMW witnessed a rise of 3.2% in its customers' demands.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] This recovery was supported by the company's adoption of widely accepted technologies and integration of third-party services such as Apple Pay and on-demand music as well as key partnerships such as its collaboration with Daimler on autonomous driving.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Additionally, BMW's strategic investment decisions which include localizing production of its SUVs to the Spartanburg plant in the U.S., placed the group in a position to easily navigate trade challenges and shifting consumer patterns.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] On 18 January 2022 BMW announced a BMW 7 Series (G11) special edition simply called "The Final V12", the last BMW series production vehicle to be fitted with a V-12 engine.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] On 5 October 2023 it was announced that BMW UK CEO Chris Brownridge would succeed Torsten Müller-Ötvös as the CEO of Rolls-Royce starting 1 December 2023, as a result of Müller-Ötvös retiring.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In January 2025, BMW announced the launch of a closed-loop recycling system for the reuse of raw materials from high-voltage batteries used in its range of electric vehicles.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In November 2024, BMW launched a partnership in Europe with SK tes, a provider of solutions to recover cobalt, nickel and lithium from used batteries for use in making new batteries.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In September 2025, BMW jointly developed an automated driving system with Qualcomm.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In January 2026, the company was reported to be among the top 30 global investors in research and development (R&D) in 2025.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW is an abbreviation for *Bayerische Motoren Werke*.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] This name is grammatically incorrect (in German, compound words must not contain spaces), which is why the grammatically correct form of the name, *Bayerische Motorenwerke* (German pronunciation: [ˈbaɪʁɪʃə moˈtoːʁənˌvɛʁkə] ⓘ) has been used in several publications and advertisements in the past.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] *Bayerische Motorenwerke* translates into English as *Bavarian Motor Works*.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The suffix AG, short for *Aktiengesellschaft*, signifies an incorporated entity owned by shareholders, akin to Inc., "Incorporated" (US) or PLC, "Public Limited Company" (UK).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The terms Beemer, Bimmer and Bee-em are sometimes used as slang for BMW in the English language and are sometimes used interchangeably for cars and motorcycles.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The circular blue and white BMW logo or roundel evolved from the circular *Rapp Motorenwerke* company logo, which featured a black ring bearing the company name surrounding the company logo, an image of a horse head on a plinth.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW retained Rapp's black ring inscribed with the company name, but the interior of the ring is quartered blue and white, reminiscent of the coat of arms and flag of Bavaria (which in turn are based on the arms of the historic House of Wittelsbach, which ruled Bavaria for many centuries).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The logo does not bear the distinctive lozenge shape found on the coat of arms, however, as local laws at the time it was introduced forbade the use of state coats of arms on commercial logos.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] A persistent myth claims that the logo is based on the image of an airplane propeller spinning in a blue sky.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] This myth likely stems from a 1929 BMW advertisement that depicted the logo superimposed on a rotating propeller.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] However, the logo predates that advertisement by 12 years.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The current iteration of the logo was introduced in 2020, removing 3D effects that had been used in previous renderings of the logo while removing the black outline encircling the roundel.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The logo is used for BMW's branding communications but it is not used on vehicles.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The slogan 'Freude am Fahren' (English: 'Sheer Driving Pleasure') has been used by BMW in most markets worldwide since 1972, when it was standardized as the company's official slogan and its English translation set for export markets.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The slogan first appeared as 'Aus Freude am Fahren' in 1965 before the opening word was dropped in 1972.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In the United States and United Kingdom, BMW instead uses 'The Ultimate Driving Machine'.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The slogan 'The Ultimate Driving Machine' was coined by BMW North America in 1974, and first used in ads celebrating its win at the 1975 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2010, this long-lived campaign was mostly supplanted by a campaign intended to make the brand more approachable and to better appeal to women, 'Joy'.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] By 2012 BMW had returned to 'The Ultimate Driving Machine'.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2023, the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO)’s Madrid Yearly Review ranked BMW's number of marks applications filled under the Madrid System as 2nd in the world, with 124 trademarks applications submitted during 2023.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW began production of motorcycle engines and then motorcycles after World War I.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Its motorcycle brand is now known as BMW Motorrad.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Their first successful motorcycle after the failed Helios and Flink, was the "R32" in 1923, though production originally began in 1921.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] This had a "boxer" twin engine, in which a cylinder projects into the air-flow from each side of the machine.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Apart from its single-cylinder models (basically to the same pattern), all its motorcycles used this distinctive layout until the early 1980s.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Many BMW's are still produced in this layout, which is designated the R Series.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The entire BMW Motorcycle production line has, since 1969, been located at the company's Berlin-Spandau factory.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] During the Second World War, BMW produced the BMW R75 motorcycle with a motor-driven sidecar attached.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Combined with a lockable differential, the vehicle was very capable off-road.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 1982 came the K Series, with a shaft drive but water-cooled and with either three or four cylinders mounted in a straight line from front to back.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Shortly after, BMW also started making the chain-driven F and G series with single and parallel twin Rotax engines.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In the early 1990s, BMW updated the airhead Boxer engine which became known as the oilhead.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2002, the oilhead engine had two spark plugs per cylinder.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2004 it added a built-in balance shaft, an increased capacity to 1,170 cc (71 cu in) and enhanced performance to 75 kW (101 hp) for the R1200GS, compared to 63 kW (84 hp) of the previous R1150GS.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] More powerful variants of the oilhead engines are available in the R1100S and R1200S, producing 73 and 91 kW (98 and 122 hp), respectively.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2004, BMW introduced the new K1200S Sports Bike which marked a departure for BMW.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] It had an engine producing 125 kW (168 hp), derived from the company's work with the Williams F1 team, and is lighter than previous K models.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Innovations include electronically adjustable front and rear suspension, and a Hossack-type front fork that BMW calls Duolever.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW introduced anti-lock brakes on production motorcycles starting in the late 1980s.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The generation of anti-lock brakes available on the 2006 and later BMW motorcycles paved the way for the introduction of electronic stability control, or anti-skid technology later in the 2007 model year.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW has been an innovator in motorcycle suspension design, taking up telescopic front suspension long before most other manufacturers.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Then it switched to an Earles fork, front suspension by swinging fork (1955 to 1969).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Most modern BMWs are truly rear swingarm, single sided at the back (compare with the regular swinging fork usually, and wrongly, called swinging arm).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Some BMWs started using yet another trademark front suspension design, the Telelever, in the early 1990s.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Like the Earles fork, the Telelever significantly reduces dive under braking.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Group, on 31 January 2013, announced that Pierer Industrie AG has bought Husqvarna Motorcycles for an undisclosed amount, which will not be revealed by either party in the future.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The company is headed by Stephan Pierer (CEO of KTM).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Pierer Industrie AG is 51% owner of KTM and 100% owner of Husqvarna.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In September 2018, BMW unveiled a new self-driving motorcycle with BMW Motorrad with a goal of using the technology to help improve road safety.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The design of the bike was inspired by the company's BMW R1200 GS model.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] All-electric vehicles and plug-in hybrid vehicles are sold under the *BMW i* sub-brand.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In addition, several plug-in hybrid models built on existing platforms have been marketed as *iPerformance* models.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Examples include the 225xe using a 1.5 L three-cylinder turbocharged petrol engine with an electric motor, the 330e/530e using a 2.0 L four-cylinder engine with an electric motor, and the 550e/750e using a 3.0 L six-cylinder engine with an electric motor.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Also, crossover and SUV plug-in hybrid models have been released using i technology: X1 xDrive25e, X2 xDrive25e, X3 xDrive30e, and X5 xDrive40e.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The *BMW M GmbH* subsidiary (called BMW Motorsport GmbH until 1993) started making high-performance versions of various BMW models in 1978.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The letter "M" is also often used in the marketing of BMW's regular models, for example the F20 M140i model, the G11 M760Li model and various optional extras called "M Sport", "M Performance" or similar.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The global BMW Headquarters in Munich is designed after the cylinder head of a four-cylinder engine.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] It was designed by Karl Schwanzer and was completed in 1972.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The building has become a European icon and was declared a protected historic building in 1999.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The main tower consists of four vertical cylinders standing next to and across from each other.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Each cylinder is divided horizontally in its center by a mold in the facade.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Notably, these cylinders do not stand on the ground; they are suspended from a central support tower.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Museum is a futuristic cauldron-shaped building, which was also designed by Karl Schwanzer and opened in 1972.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The interior has a spiral theme and the roof is a 40-metre diameter BMW logo.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Welt, the company's exhibition space in Munich, was designed by Coop Himmelb(l)au and opened in 2007.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] It includes a showroom and lifting platforms where a customer's new car is theatrically unveiled to the customer.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 1975, sculptor Alexander Calder was commissioned to paint the BMW 3.0 CSL racing car driven by Hervé Poulain at the 24 Hours of Le Mans, which became the first in the series of BMW Art Cars.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Since Calder's work of art, many other renowned artists throughout the world have created BMW Art Cars, including David Hockney, Jenny Holzer, Roy Lichtenstein, Robert Rauschenberg, Frank Stella, and Andy Warhol.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] To date, a total of 19 BMW Art Cars, based on both racing and regular production vehicles, have been created.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW sponsors a number of awards in the visual arts.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] These include the BMW Art Journey award, which honors a young or mid-career artist in collaboration with Art Basel, and the BMW Painting Award, which was created to promote painting in Spain by finding new talent and showcasing their work.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW was the principal sponsor of the 1998 *The Art of the Motorcycle* exhibition at various Guggenheim museums, though the financial relationship between BMW and the Guggenheim Foundation was criticised in many quarters.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2012, BMW began sponsoring Independent Collectors production of the *BMW Art Guide*, which is the first global guide to private and publicly accessible collections of contemporary art worldwide.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The fourth edition, released in 2016, features 256 collections from 43 countries.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW also has local assembly operation using complete knock-down (CKD) components in Brazil, Thailand, Russia, Egypt, Indonesia, Malaysia and India.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In the UK, BMW has a Mini factory near Oxford, plants in Swindon and Hams Hall, and Rolls-Royce vehicle assembly at Goodwood.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2020, these facilities were shut down for the period from 23 March to 17 April due to the coronavirus outbreak.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The BMW group (including Mini and Rolls-Royce) produced 1,366,838 automobiles in 2006 and then 1,481,253 automobiles in 2010.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Motorcycles are being produced at the company's Berlin factory, which earlier had produced aircraft engines for Siemens.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] By 2011, about 56% of BMW-brand vehicles produced were powered by petrol engines and the remaining 44% by diesel engines.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Of those petrol vehicles, about 27% were four-cylinder models and about nine percent are eight-cylinder models, the overwhelming majority being sixes.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] On average, 9,000 vehicles per day exit BMW plants, and 63% are transported by rail.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In November 2016, BMW recalled 136,000 2007–2012 model year U.S. cars for fuel pump wiring problems possibly resulting in fuel leak and engine stalling or restarting issues.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2018, BMW recalled 106,000 diesel vehicles in South Korea with a defective exhaust gas recirculation module, which caused 39 engine fires.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The recall was then expanded to 324,000 more cars in Europe.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Following the recall in South Korea, the government banned cars which had not yet been inspected from driving on public roads.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] This affected up to 25% of the recalled cars, where the owners had been notified but the cars had not yet been inspected.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW is reported to have been aware since 2016 that more than 4% of the affected cars in South Korea had experienced failures in the EGR coolers, leading to approximately 20 owners suing the company.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW made a six-year sponsorship deal with the United States Olympic Committee in July 2010.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In golf, BMW has sponsored various events, including the PGA Championship since 2007, the Italian Open from 2009 to 2012, the BMW Masters in China from 2012 to 2015 and the BMW International Open in Munich since 1989.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In rugby, BMW sponsored the South Africa national rugby union team from 2011 to 2015.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] DriveNow was a joint-venture between BMW and Sixt that operated in Europe from 2011 until 2019.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] By December 2012, DriveNow operated over 1,000 vehicles, in five cities and with approximately 60,000 customers.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2012, the BMW-owned subsidiary Alphabet began a corporate car-sharing service in Europe called AlphaCity.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The ReachNow car-sharing service was launched in Seattle in April 2016.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] ReachNow currently operates in Seattle, Portland and Brooklyn.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2018, BMW announced the launching of a pilot car subscription service for the United States called Access by BMW (its first one for the country), in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In January 2021, the company said that Access by BMW was "suspended".
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The first BMW production facility in China was opened in 2004, as a result of a joint venture between BMW and Brilliance Auto.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The plant was opened in the Shenyang industrial area and produces 3 Series and 5 Series models for the Chinese market.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2012, a second factory was opened in Shenyang.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Between January and November 2014, BMW sold 415,200 vehicles in China, through a network of over 440 BMW stores and 100 Mini stores.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] On 7 October 2021, BMW announced it would begin additional production of the X5 in China.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In February 2022, BMW invested an additional $4.2 billion into the Chinese joint venture, increasing its stake from 50% to 75%, becoming one of the first foreign automakers holding majority stake in China.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In June 2022, BMW announced a new plant project in Lydia, Shenyang designed for electric vehicles.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] It will become BMW Group's largest single project in China, costing 15 billion yuan (2.13 billion euros).
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The investment amount was raised by a further 10 billion yuan (US$1.4 billion) in November 2022, following German Chancellor Olaf Scholz's visit to China.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] On 31 July 2018, BMW announced to build a 1 billion euro car factory in Hungary.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The plant, to be built near Debrecen, will have a production capacity of 150,000 cars a year.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In July 2014, BMW announced it was establishing a plant in Mexico, in the city and state of San Luis Potosí involving an investment of $1 billion.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The plant will employ 1,500 people, and produce 150,000 cars annually.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The Mini Convertible, Mini Countryman and BMW X1 were produced in the Netherlands at the VDL Nedcar factory in Born up until its closure on February 16, 2024.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The factory was closed after BMW did not renew its contract with VDL Nedcar.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Long-term orders for the Mini Countryman ended in 2020.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMWs have been assembled in South Africa since 1968, when Praetor Monteerders' plant was opened in Rosslyn, near Pretoria.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW initially bought shares in the company, before fully acquiring it in 1975; in so doing, the company became *BMW South Africa*, the first wholly owned subsidiary of BMW to be established outside Germany.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Unlike United States manufacturers, such as Ford and GM, which divested from the country in the 1980s, BMW retained full ownership of its operations in South Africa.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Following the end of apartheid in 1994, and the lowering of import tariffs, BMW South Africa ended local production of the 5 Series and 7 Series, in order to concentrate on production of the 3 Series for the export market.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] South African–built BMWs are now exported to right hand drive markets including Japan, Australia, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, and Hong Kong, as well as Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Since 1997, BMW South Africa has produced vehicles in left-hand drive for export to Taiwan, the United States and Iran, as well as South America.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The plant code (position 11 in the VIN) for South African built models is "N".
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW cars have been officially sold in the United States since 1956 and manufactured in the United States since 1994.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The first BMW dealership in the United States opened in 1975.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2016, BMW was the twelfth highest selling brand in the United States.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The manufacturing plant in Greer, South Carolina has the highest production of the BMW plants worldwide, currently producing approximately 1,500 vehicles per day.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The models produced at the Spartanburg plant are the X3, X4, X5, X6, X7 and XM SUV models.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In addition to the South Carolina manufacturing facility, BMW's North American companies include sales, marketing, design, and financial services operations in the United States, Mexico, Canada and Latin America.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] On 9 October 2014, BMW's new complete knock-down (CKD) assembly plant in Araquari, assembled its first car— an F30 3 Series.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The cars assembled at Araquari are the F20 1 Series, F30 3 Series, F48 X1, F25 X3 and Mini Countryman.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Bavarian Auto Group became the importer of the BMW and Mini brands in 2003.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Since 2005, the 3 Series, 5 Series, 7 Series, X1 and X3 models sold in Egypt are assembled from complete knock-down components at the BMW plant in Cairo.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW India was established in 2006 as a sales subsidiary with a head office located in Gurugram.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] A BMW complete knock-down assembly plant was opened in Chennai in 2007, assembling Indian-market 3 Series, 5 Series, 7 Series, X1, X3, X5, Mini Countryman and motorcycle models.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] The 20 Million Euro plant aims to produce 1,700 cars per year.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Indonesia was established in 2001 as a subsidiary with a head office located in Central Jakarta.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW's complete knock-down (CKD) assembly plant in Kedah.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Assembled Malaysia-market 1 Series, 3 Series, 5 Series, 7 Series, X1, X3, X4, X5, X6 and Mini Countryman since 2008.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Russian-market 3 Series and 5 Series cars are assembled from complete knock-down components in Kaliningrad beginning in 1999.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In March 2022, BMW withdrew from the Russian market, ceased new car sales in Russia, and ceased production within Russia, in response to the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In Uruguay, Spanish-born businessman José Arijón founded Convex (later Camur), which assembled BMW cars from 1965 to 1992.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] Four models were produced: the 1600, 2002, 3 Series and 5 Series, totalling 12,000 units.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW's first dealership in Canada, located in Ottawa, was opened in 1969.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 1986, BMW established a head office in Canada.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW sold 28,149 vehicles in Canada in 2008.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Japan Corp, a wholly owned subsidiary, imports and distributes BMW vehicles in Japan.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Philippines, an owned subsidiary of San Miguel Corporation, is the official importer and distributor of BMW in the Philippines.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW sold 920 vehicles in the Philippines in 2019.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Korea imports BMW vehicles in South Korea with more than fifty service centers to fully cater to South Korean customers.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW Korea has its own driving center near Incheon International Airport.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW car represented almost 10% of all new cars registered in 2025, making it the third most popular car brand.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] BMW has received criticism for attempting to lock vehicle hardware features behind subscription fees.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2018, BMW stated at the Detroit Auto Show that it will start charging users a subscription fee for Apple Car Play.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] After receiving widespread criticism, BMW removed the subscription.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] In 2022, BMW announced that it will start charging owners $18 a month to use heated seats.
[src:bristol-407/bmw] They removed the feature in 2023 after it was criticised.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] The **Bristol 400** is a luxury car made by the Bristol Cars division of the Bristol Aeroplane Company.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] Manufactured from 1947 to 1950, it was the first model of car that the company made.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] As World War II progressed, Bristol Aircraft considered its future, which resulted in forming a car division in 1945, later becoming the Bristol Cars company in its own right.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] Engineers from Bristol inspected the Soviet-controlled BMW factory at Eisenach in the Soviet occupation zone in Germany, and returned to Britain with plans for the BMW 327 and the BMW six-cylinder engine as official war reparations.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] Bristol then employed BMW engineer Fritz Fiedler to lead its engine development team.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] In 1946 Bristol Aircraft acquired a majority shareholding in Frazer Nash, which in the 1930s held a licence to build the BMW 328.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] In 1947 the newly-formed Bristol Cars released its 400 coupé.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] It is a lengthened version of the BMW 327, and features BMW's double-kidney radiator grille.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] Bristol based the 400 on the best features of two outstanding pre-war BMWs: the engine of the 328, and the chassis of the 326.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] These were covered with a mainly steel body but with aluminium bonnet, door and boot skins inspired by the 327.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] The 400 has a slightly modified version of BMW's six-cylinder pushrod engine of 1,971 cc (bore 66 mm, stroke 96 mm).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] This engine, considered advanced for its time due to its hemispherical combustion chambers and very short inlet and exhaust ports, develops 80 horsepower at 4,500 rpm, and gives the car a top speed of about 148 km/h (92 mph), with acceleration to match.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] In order to form a hemispherical combustion chamber, the valves are positioned at an angle to the head.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] In order to drive both sets of valves from a single camshaft, the Bristol engine uses a system of rods, followers and bell-cranks to drive the valves on the far side of the engine from the camshaft.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] Owners soon found that setting and maintaining the numerous clearances in the system was difficult, but vital to keep the engine in tune.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] The gearbox is a four-speed manual with synchromesh on the upper three ratios and a freewheel in first.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] The 400 is the only Bristol that has a steel and aluminium skin.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] It has all flat glass, apart from the curved rear window, which is glazed in Perspex, and was available to specification with a top hinge.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] This was very welcome on warmer climate export markets, where the sliding door windows provided only marginal ventilation to the occupants.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] The 400 has independent front suspension with a transverse leaf spring and a live axle, located by an A-bracket over the differential case, and longitudinal torsion bars with transverse arms and brackets at the rear.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] It has a lengthy 2,895 mm (114.0 in) wheelbase and a very BMW-like grille at the front of its long bonnet.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] The passenger area is very short, with the spare tyre mounted inside the boot on the first cars.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] In later 400s the spare wheel is mounted on the rear hinged boot lid, inside an aluminium cover.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] Battista Pininfarina designed an alternative body for the 400.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-400] Its lines prefigure the 400's successor model, the 401, which Bristol launched in 1948.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The **Bristol 401** saloon and **Bristol 402** cabriolet are British luxury grand tourers, produced between 1948 and 1953 by Bristol Cars, an offshoot of the Bristol Aeroplane Company They were developed from the Bristol 400, which continued in production alongside the 401 and 402 until 1950.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The 401 and 402 use an improved version of the BMW 328 hemispherical-head engine and its unusual arrangement of two separate pushrods to operate the exhaust valves, necessitated by the hemispherical combustion chambers and opposite facing valves, as used in the 400.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] However, the styling was an advance on that first Bristol model.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] It was inspired by a Milanese designer, Carrozzeria Touring, and its most notable feature is that the door handles are not exposed.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The doors are opened by pressing a button in the door.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The body is more spacious than the 400, and is a full five-seater.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] At the front the 401 and 402 are also distinctive, with their headlights positioned quite a distance toward the centre-line of the body, either side of the narrow grille, which resembles BMW grille a little less than does the 400's.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] They are also deeply curved at the front: this, along with the then-unique door handle arrangement, is believed to give the 401 a drag coefficient of less than Cd 0.36 – competitive even by today's standards and remarkable for the time.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The engine is the same 2-litre in-line six-cylinder petrol unit as in the 400, but upgraded with improved Solex carburettors to increase power by 5 bhp (3.7 kW) to 85 bhp (63 kW).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] This improved the performance further beyond what was achieved by the aerodynamics.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The suspension is independent at the front, using a transverse leaf spring and wishbones.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The rigid axle at the rear has torsion bars.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The brakes are Lockheed hydraulic, with 11 in (279 mm) drums all round.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] Bristol made 611 401s, which is still the largest production run of any Bristol model.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] However, it made only 23 402s, which makes it one of the rarest historic cars of its era.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] In a recent survey, 13 of those 23 were accounted for.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] A saloon tested by *The Motor* magazine in 1952 recorded a top speed of 97.3 mph (156.6 km/h), and accelerated from 0 to 60 mph (97 km/h) in 15.1 seconds.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] A fuel consumption of 20.8 miles per imperial gallon (13.6 L/100 km; 17.3 mpg‑US) was recorded.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] The test car cost £3,532 including taxes.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] Referring to that road test in a 1971 "classic car" feature, the journal summarised the 401 as a "Medium-sized car offering very high standards of comfort and performance".
[src:bristol-407/bristol-401] Four examples of a 401 Cabriolet with styling by Pininfarina were also built.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] The **Bristol 403** is a luxury car which was produced from 1953 to 1955 by British manufacturer Bristol Aeroplane Co.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] (whose car division later became Bristol Cars).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] The 403 was the third of the eventual five series of Bristols powered by the BMW-derived pushrod straight-six engine.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] It replaced the Bristol 401 and 402 in 1953 and continued in production for two years.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] It retained much the same styling as the 401, but featured many mechanical improvements compared to that model.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] The 1971 cc six-cylinder engine was modified through the use of bigger valves and larger main bearings with a diameter of 54 mm as against 51 mm on the 400 and 401, which increased the power output to 100 hp (75 kW) as against 85 hp (63 kW) on the 401.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] The acceleration was markedly improved: the 403 could reach 60 miles per hour (97 km/h) in 13.4 seconds as against 16.4 seconds for the 401.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] The 403 had top speed of 104 miles per hour (167 km/h).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] To cope with this increased power, an anti-roll bar was fitted on the front suspension and improved drum brakes known as "Alfins" (Aluminum finned) were fitted.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] Early models had them on all wheels, but Bristol thought the car was over-braked and they were thus restricted to the front wheels on later 403s.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] The 403 was the last Bristol to feature a BMW-style radiator grille.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-403] It is also noteworthy for having two extra headlamps at the side, almost pre-dating the adoption of the four-headlamp layout in larger cars (Bristol themselves adopted it with the 411 in the late 1960s).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The **Bristol 404** and **Bristol 405** are British luxury cars which were manufactured by the Bristol Aeroplane Company.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The models were successors to the Bristol 403.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The 404 was a two-seat coupé and the 405 was available as a four-seat, four-door saloon and as a four-seat, two-door drophead coupé.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] Unlike previous or later Bristol models, there is considerable confusion in nomenclature when it comes to the Bristol 404 and 405.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The 404 was a very short-wheelbase car introduced in 1953, whereas the longer 405 was introduced in 1955.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The wheelbases are 8 feet (2,438 mm) for the 404 and 9 feet 6 inches (2,896 mm) for the 405.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The 405 itself was seen in two versions.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The more common (265 of 308 built) is a four-door saloon built on the standard chassis of the previous Bristols, whilst the 405 drophead coupé or 405D (43 built) had a convertible body by Abbotts of Farnham.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The body used aluminium panels over a steel and ash frame, mounted on a substantial horse-shoe shaped chassis.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] Most cars built had a highly tuned (through advanced valve timing) version of the 2 litre six-cylinder engine called the 100C which developed 125 bhp (93 kW) as against the 105 bhp (78 kW) of the standard 100B 405 engine.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] Even the 105 bhp engine was fitted with Solex triple downdraft carburettors.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] With UK fuel supplies no longer restricted to the low-octane wartime "pool petrol", all engines for the 404 and 405 came with higher compression ratios than predecessor Bristols — 8.5:1 as against 7.5:1.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] Rack and pinion steering was fitted and the car's handling won accolades from press reports when the car was introduced (and subsequently).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] Compared to the 403, the 404 and 405 had an improved gearbox with much shorter gear lever, which improved what was already by the standards of the day a very slick gearchange.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The 405, though *not* the 404, had overdrive as standard apart from the earliest models, and front disc brakes became an option apart from the earliest models, and were fitted to almost all 405 drophead coupés.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] A few late 405s were fitted with the higher torque 2.2 litre engine introduced in the later 406.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] Externally, a notable feature of the 404 and 405 was the abandonment of the BMW-style radiator grille for one much more like an aero-engine.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The 405, although the only four-door car ever built by Bristol, had styling that the company was later to refine for many years on their later Chrysler V8-engined cars during the 1960s.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] It was also the model that introduced the Bristol feature of sizable lockers in the front wings accessed externally by gullwing doors.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The locker on the nearside held the spare wheel and jack, whilst that on the offside housed the battery and fuse panel.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] In the 1955 comedy film *Josephine and Men*, one of the main characters, Alan, played by Donald Sinden, drives a maroon 405.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] A maroon 405, registration TEL 808 appears prominently in the music video for Swing Out Sister "Forever Blue" (1989).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] A silver 405, described as a 1955 Bristol, is driven by the character Jack Kerruish (played by Kevin Whately) in the first three series of *Peak Practice*, set in the early 1990s in the Peak District.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] A maroon 405 is featured prominently in the 2009 independent film *An Education*, directed by Lone Scherfig, which is a period film set in 1961 in the London suburbs.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] The vicar, Sidney Chambers (played by James Norton), was given a lift in a maroon 405, at the beginning of *Grantchester*, series 3, episode 5 (2017).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] Daniel Day-Lewis is featured driving a maroon 405 around Whitby, North Yorkshire, in the film *Phantom Thread*, directed by Paul Thomas Anderson and released on Christmas Day 2017.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-404-and-405] In the 2017 Sony Pictures film adaptation of Agatha Christie's *Crooked House*, private detective Charles Hayward (Max Irons) uses a maroon 405.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The **Bristol 407** is a sports tourer car produced by British manufacturer Bristol Cars between 1961 and 1963.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] It was the first Bristol model to be made by the company after separating from the Bristol Aeroplane Company, which had built all previous Bristol models.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Outwardly it resembled the 406, on which it was based, and which had been produced between 1958 and 1961.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Unlike its predecessors, the Bristol 406 suffered from a lack of power: Bristol's BMW-derived 105 bhp (78 kW) inline six-cylinder engine (type 110) no longer enabled the 1.5-ton car to achieve the sporty driving performance that distinguished earlier Bristol models.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] A further increase in performance of the engine, the concept of which dated back to before the Second World War, could no longer be achieved.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Bristol was therefore looking for a new engine in the second half of the 1950s.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] First, the company started to develop its own, new engine, designated type 160.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The key requirement was a six-cylinder configuration and a displacement of 3.0 to 3.5 litres, similar to that of contemporary Alvis engines.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] However, the performance of the first prototypes was not convincing; in any case, the parent company was of the opinion that the financial expense of the new construction was not commensurate with its benefits.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] In 1959, Bristol tested another in-line Armstrong Siddeley six-cylinder engine.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The 4.0 litre engine was standard in the Armstrong Siddeley Star Sapphire and produced 165 bhp.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Bristol equipped a 406 with this engine and carried out some test runs at the factory.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] However, there was no takeup into series production.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The prototype went on sale and was in regular use until 1975.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] In 2015 it was rediscovered in an unrestored condition.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] In the end, Bristol decided to use Chrysler's US eight-cylinder engine.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] It is not clear from whom the initiative to use American engines came.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Bristol owner Tony Crook repeatedly told the following story: Actually, Bristol only wanted to order a Torque-Flite automatic transmission for test purposes.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] To the surprise of the Bristol employees, Chrysler would have included an in-house eight-cylinder in addition to the ordered gearbox.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Bristol then subjected the engine to in-depth tests and decided in favour of using the American engine in view of the high performance and cost-effectiveness of the concept – which meant saving its own development costs.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] To further cost saving, Bristol did not source the engines directly from the US but from Canada, a member of the Commonwealth.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] This meant that there were no import duties when the engines were transferred to the UK.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The Bristol engine was based on an older American engine, which had made its debut at Chrysler's Plymouth brand in 1956 and originally had a displacement of 260 CID (4.2 litres).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Bristol obtained the engine blocks from the USA and had them completed by hand in a Canadian Chrysler workshop.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] At the same time, a series of far-reaching modifications were carried out to distinguish the Bristol engines from their large-series counterparts: The engine bore was increased from 3.56 inches to 3.87 inches.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] This resulted in a displacement of 5.2 litres – with only a marginally changed stroke – as Chrysler did not have an engine of the appropriate size in its series portfolio.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The engines were also given a new cylinder head of Bristol's own design, replacing the original "polyspherical" Plymouth head.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The engine delivered an output of 250 bhp (186 kW) after the manual modifications, which more than doubled the performance potential compared to the previous model.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Bristol was again on the way to becoming a sports car manufacturer.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The switch to American engines was not without problems, although this step was not without a model: Facel Vega from France had already taken this route a few years earlier, and the British competitor Jensen was about to do the same.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The conservative British clientele was nevertheless sceptical and, according to Tony Crook, quite a few are said to have seen it as a sin.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Most critics, however, were reconciled by the outstanding driving performance of the car.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Bristol's long-serving 2.0 litre six-cylinder engine continued to be built for some time after the introduction of the 407.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] It was primarily supplied to AC Cars, where it was installed in the Ace, Aceca, and Greyhound models until the end of 1962.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The new V8 engine was mated to a TorqueFlite automatic gearbox as the only transmission option.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The transmission had three forward speeds and a torque converter.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The only changes were very subtle, comprising a single horizontal bar on the somewhat enlarged radiator grille, which had been steadily increased in size from the 405 to the 406 through to the 407, plus two exhaust pipes instead of one at the rear.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] However, under the bonnet of the 407 was not the old BMW-derived six-cylinder engine that was now inadequate for Bristols to be able to compete in performance with other British makes of luxury car.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Replacing the old six-cylinder engine was a 5,130 cc (313 cu in) Chrysler V8, built in Canada, fitted with a new camshaft and mechanical tappets (lifters) of Bristol design.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] It re-established Bristol's credentials in the field of performance cars.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The engine gave the 407 a maximum speed of over 125 mph (201 km/h) and established a tradition that continued until the manufacturer's bankruptcy in 2011.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The other major change vis-à-vis the 406 lay in the front suspension.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Gone were the transverse leaf springs that were inadequate to provide effective handling given a higher weight and also the higher speeds which the 407 was capable of; in its place were coil springs.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] This basic suspension design was to be used on all future eight-cylinder Bristols, though there were to be major refinements from the 603 onwards.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Gone also was rack and pinion steering, which inhibited the 407's handling.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The bodywork on the 407 and subsequent models was built by bus body builder Park Royal Vehicles who also did trimming and finishing on some of those produced.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The Bristol 407 remained in production until the summer of 1963.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Around 300 vehicles are said to have been produced during this period.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] A handful of cars received bespoke bodywork, by Viotti and Zagato.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] As in the case of the Bristol 406, Bristol also had a special body designed by Zagato for the 407.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The result, the Bristol 407 GTZ Zagato, had nothing to do with the 406 Zagato.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The new design had an elongated, rounded body with a very low belt line, a "hip swing" over the rear wheels and a lush glazed hatchback.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The car was significantly lighter than the factory 407 and reached top speeds of over 200 km/ h.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The Bristol 407 GTZ Zagato was first exhibited at the Earls Court Motorshow in October 1961.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] However, the car was not at the Bristol booth, but at the nondescript Zagato booth.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The author of the project was again Anthony Crook (and not Bristol Cars Ltd.).
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] It only took 10 weeks from the idea to the finished product.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] That wasn't just true for the radiator grille with a crest-shaped shield, which was borrowed from a Lancia Flaminia Supersport.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The car was welcomed in a friendly manner, but the few journalists who were allowed to drive the car criticised the front-heavy construction.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The extremely light Zagato body combined with the heavy weight of the American engine led to an unfavourable weight distribution.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Tony Crook, who had initially hoped for a few orders, abandoned the project in the summer of 1962 because the plant could not resolve the weight distribution problems.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The 407 GTZ was unique and still exists today.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] Another special model was a four-seater convertible that the Carrozzeria Viotti from Turin produced on a bare chassis of the 407.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The body was relatively simple and took out some perspective, anticipating the design of the Fiat 1500 Spider.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The car was first presented at the Viotti booth at the 1960 Turin Motor Show.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] This was followed by another showing in the UK, this time at the Bristol Cars stand.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The actor Peter Sellers, who valued Bristol vehicles, owned the car for a short while.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] It has a steel body, a unique feature for a Bristol and still exists today.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] The British "Motor" magazine tested a 407 in 1961 and recorded a top speed of 125.2 mph (201.5 km/h) and acceleration from 0-60 mph (97 km/h) in 9.2 seconds.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] A "touring" fuel consumption of 17.5 miles per imperial gallon (16.1 L/100 km; 14.6 mpg‑US) was recorded.
[src:bristol-407/bristol-407] On the home market, as tested, it cost £5141 including taxes of £1616.
